<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Zooxanthellate, absence of mineral incrustations in the column/coenenchyme (excluding superficial surface attachments) brachycnemic zoantharians inhabiting the outside of eunicid worms, with a 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘budding’">'budding'</normalizedToken>
method of asexual reproduction (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" author="Reimer, JD" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" refId="B233" refString="Reimer, JD, Ishikawa, SA, Hirose, M, 2011b. New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41(2): 313-323. https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" title="New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41 (2): 313 - 323." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" year="2011 b">Reimer et al. 2011b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Specimens examined with a discontiguous mesogleal sphincter muscle (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0406-1" author="Swain, TD" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="B284" refString="Swain, TD, Schellinger, JL, Strimaitis, AM, Reuter, KE, 2015. Evolution of anthozoan polyp retraction mechanisms: convergent functional morphology and evolutionary allometry of the marginal musculature in order Zoanthidea (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). BMC Evolutionary Biology 15(123): 1-19. https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0406-1" title="Evolution of anthozoan polyp retraction mechanisms: convergent functional morphology and evolutionary allometry of the marginal musculature in order Zoanthidea (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). BMC Evolutionary Biology 15 (123): 1 - 19." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-015-0406-1" year="2015">Swain et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Acrozoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a long and complicated taxonomic history. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" author="Reimer, JD" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" refId="B233" refString="Reimer, JD, Ishikawa, SA, Hirose, M, 2011b. New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41(2): 313-323. https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" title="New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41 (2): 313 - 323." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" year="2011 b">Reimer et al. (2011b)</bibRefCitation>
discussed that &quot;despite its very similar appearance, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus australiae" order="Zoantharia" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Acrozoanthus australiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was placed into a genus separate from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" class="Anthozoa" family="Epizoanthidae" genus="Zoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Zoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to the presence of an axial skeleton 
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="7" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
<bibRefCitation author="Saville-Kent, W" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="B254" refString="Saville-Kent, W, 1893. Coral and Coral Animals. pp. 139-203, pls. 21-30. In: The Great Barrier Reef of Australia; Its Products and Potentialities. Containing-An Account, With Copious Coloured and Photographic Illustrations (The Latter Here Produced for the First Time), of the Corals and Coral Reefs, Pearl and Pearl-shell, Beche-de-mer, Other Fishing Industries, and the Marine Fauna of the Australian Great Barrier Region. W.H. Allen &amp; Co., London, xvii + [1] + 387 pp., pls. 1-48, 1-16. [&gt; 24 Feb 1893 (preface, p. xii); &lt; 4 Mar 1893 (Anonymous 1893: 249)]" title="Coral and Coral Animals. pp. 139 - 203, pls. 21 - 30. In: The Great Barrier Reef of Australia; Its Products and Potentialities. Containing-An Account, With Copious Coloured and Photographic Illustrations (The Latter Here Produced for the First Time), of the Corals and Coral Reefs, Pearl and Pearl-shell, Beche-de-mer, Other Fishing Industries, and the Marine Fauna of the Australian Great Barrier Region. W. H. Allen &amp; Co., London, xvii + [1] + 387 pp., pls. 1 - 48, 1 - 16. [&gt; 24 Feb 1893 (preface, p. xii); &lt;4 Mar 1893 (Anonymous 1893: 249)]" year="1893">Saville-Kent 1893</bibRefCitation>
). Later it was shown that this skeleton was in fact a result of habitat preference as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Acrozoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits the outside of eunicid worm tubes, and the genus was subsequently merged back again into the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" class="Anthozoa" family="Epizoanthidae" genus="Zoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Zoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Haddon, AC" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="B125" refString="Haddon, AC, 1895. Branched worm-tubes and Acrozoanthus. Scientific Proceedings of the Royal Dublin Society 8(4): 344-346. [27 Jul 1895 (p. 344)]" title="Branched worm-tubes and Acrozoanthus. Scientific Proceedings of the Royal Dublin Society 8 (4): 344 - 346. [27 Jul 1895 (p. 344)]" year="1895">Haddon 1895</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequent to its original description, this species was not mentioned in literature again until its rediscovery by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" author="Ryland, JS" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" refId="B245" refString="Ryland, JS, 1997. Reproduction in Zoanthidea (Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). Invertebrate Reproduction and Development 31(1-3): 177-188. https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" title="Reproduction in Zoanthidea (Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). Invertebrate Reproduction and Development 31 (1 - 3): 177 - 188." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" year="1997">Ryland (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, based on examination of a single specimen. Further work by Ryland and co-workers described the nematocysts of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus australiae" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Acrozoanthus australiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0022293031000155179" author="Ryland, JS" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="B251" refString="Ryland, JS, Brasseur, MM, Lancaster, JE, 2004. Use of cnidae in taxonomy: implications from a study of Acrozanthus australiae (Hexacorallia, Zoanthidea). Journal of Natural History 38(10): 1193-1223. https://doi.org/10.1080/0022293031000155179" title="Use of cnidae in taxonomy: implications from a study of Acrozanthus australiae (Hexacorallia, Zoanthidea). Journal of Natural History 38 (10): 1193 - 1223." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0022293031000155179" year="2004">Ryland et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
) and also an unusual 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘budding’">'budding'</normalizedToken>
method of asexual reproduction (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" author="Ryland, JS" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" refId="B245" refString="Ryland, JS, 1997. Reproduction in Zoanthidea (Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). Invertebrate Reproduction and Development 31(1-3): 177-188. https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" title="Reproduction in Zoanthidea (Anthozoa: Hexacorallia). Invertebrate Reproduction and Development 31 (1 - 3): 177 - 188." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/07924259.1997.9672575" year="1997">Ryland 1997</bibRefCitation>
), which was theorized to potentially confirm the placement of this species in its own genus&quot;.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Molecular phylogenetic data indicate that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Acrozoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" class="Anthozoa" family="Epizoanthidae" genus="Zoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Zoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" author="Reimer, JD" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" refId="B233" refString="Reimer, JD, Ishikawa, SA, Hirose, M, 2011b. New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41(2): 313-323. https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" title="New records and molecular characterization of Acrozoanthus (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Hexacorallia) and its endosymbionts (Symbiodinium spp.) from Taiwan. Marine Biodiversity 41 (2): 313 - 323." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-010-0069-5" year="2011 b">Reimer et al. 2011b</bibRefCitation>
) monophyly. However, due to a need for more detailed investigations, we refrain from synonymising 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saville-Kent" authorityYear="1893" class="Anthozoa" family="Zoanthidae" genus="Acrozoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acrozoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Acrozoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1801" class="Anthozoa" family="Epizoanthidae" genus="Zoanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zoanthus" order="Zoantharia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Zoanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
